`bwrap/` translates a caller-assembled `BwrapConfig` into the exact `bwrap` argv that isolates a cage process: no network except a proxy socket, target project bound read-write at its real host path, secrets masked read-only, toolchain bound read-only at unmodified host paths. Depending on this subtree gets you one function, `build_bwrap_args`, plus the fixed in-cage path constants; everything else is internal wiring.

The coupling that matters: `config.rs` defines both the `BwrapConfig` struct and the path constants (`CAGE_BIN`, `CAGE_RULES_PATH`, `CAGE_RUN_DIR`, `API_SOCK_NAME`, etc.), and `build.rs` consumes both to emit argv in a fixed five-step order (`add_base_isolation` → `add_workspace` → `add_toolchain` → `add_tools_and_rules` → `add_envs`) where ordering is semantically load-bearing for bwrap (`--clearenv` must precede `--setenv`). Changing a constant in `config.rs` silently changes mount paths in `build.rs`'s output — the two files must be edited together. `mod.rs` restates the mount plan in prose as the canonical spec; if `build.rs` changes the layout, `mod.rs`'s doc comment must be updated too, since nothing enforces the sync mechanically. `discover.rs` is a separate concern — it walks the target's `crates/*` for `src`/`test` dirs to inform tmpfs overlay config — and doesn't touch `BwrapConfig` or argv construction directly, but its output presumably feeds config assembly upstream.

Subtree-spanning invariant: the whole module is pure (no I/O, no subprocess exec) except `discover.rs`, which does read the filesystem to enumerate crate directories — this is the one exception to the "build.rs/config.rs are pure" convention. `mask_file` must be a real empty file, never `/dev/null`, since binds are `nodev`. `env` in `BwrapConfig` is exhaustive because `--clearenv` runs first.

No `intent.md` exists for this directory, so no divergence can be assessed.